function App() {
  let mystyle = {
    color: "blue",
    backgroundColor: "aliceblue"
  };

  return (
    <>
      <h4 style={mystyle}>using function to print and adjust color</h4>
    </>
  );
}


function App() {: This declares a functional component named App.

let mystyle = { color: "blue", backgroundColor: "aliceblue" };: This line defines a JavaScript object named mystyle, which holds the styling properties for the <h4> element that follows.
In this case, it sets the text color to "blue" and the background color to "aliceblue".

return (: The beginning of the JSX block that the component will render.
JSX is a syntax extension for JavaScript, often used in React for defining the structure and content of components.

<>: This is a shorthand for a React fragment.
A fragment is used to group multiple elements without introducing an additional parent element in the DOM. It's often used when you want to return multiple elements from a component.

<h4 style={mystyle}>using function to print and adjust color</h4>: This is an <h4> (header 4) element being rendered.
The style attribute is used to apply the CSS styles defined in the mystyle object to this element. So, the text inside the <h4> will have a blue color and the background will be a light blue color ("aliceblue").

</>: Closing the fragment.

);: Closing parenthesis for the return statement.

So, in summary, this code defines a functional component named App that renders an <h4> element with the text "using function to print and adjust color".
The text is displayed in blue color with a light blue background, as specified in the mystyle object.
The use of fragments (<>...</>) allows multiple JSX elements to be returned without introducing an extra wrapping element in the rendered output.
